\begin_layout Section
Discrimination of Signal and Background
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As an input to multivariate classification techniques, input variables have
 to be chosen.
 The choice for a certain variable which is e.g.
 based on the event kinematics is often made according to its discrimination
 power within the multivariate training phase.
 This is applicable if one is solely interested in the best background discrimin
ation with a minimum set of variables.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For this analyses it is crucial to minimize a potential bias on the shape
 of the differential distributions after a discriminator requirement is
 applied.
 A shape bias can occur if a multivariate method becomes sensitive to the
 specific coupling scenario which is used for the training of the classifier.
 Non-correlated variables to the 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos\theta_{\mathrm{B,\, X}}$
\end_inset

 angles are chosen as input variables.
 This is not a sufficient condition to obtain a bias free discriminator.
 The actual bias is evaluated by using the dedicated set of anomalous coupling
 samples.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Choice of Independent Variables
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One way of estimating a correlation between two variables is provided by
 the Pearson product-moment correlation coefficient.
 It is calculated between the variables 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 by
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
r=\frac{\sum_{i}\left(x_{i}-\bar{x}\right)\left(y_{i}-\bar{y}\right)}{\sqrt{\sum_{i}\left(x_{i}-\bar{x}\right)^{2}}\sqrt{\sum_{i}\left(y_{i}-\bar{y}\right)^{2}}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{x}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{y}$
\end_inset

 are the means of the distributions 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{y}$
\end_inset

.
 This correlation estimator is only sensitive to a linear dependence between
 two variables.
 To detect even non-linear dependencies a more sophisticated method is used.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An algorithm to test an independence hypothesis has been proposed in reference
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "independentAlgo"

\end_inset

.
 It is based on a 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi^{2}$
\end_inset

-test.
 In the following, this algorithm is elaborated.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The algorithm can be divided into two steps.
 Suppose the distributions of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 are subjected to testing for independence between them.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First, the distributions of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 are flattened.
 This is performed by constructing a copula in which 
\begin_inset Formula $x\rightarrow\tilde{x}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y\rightarrow\tilde{y}$
\end_inset

 are transformed so that the distributions are only within the interval
 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{x},\,\tilde{y}\in[0;\,1]$
\end_inset

.
 For a finite amount 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,\, y)$
\end_inset

 pairs this can be performed by sorting 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}=(x_{1},\ldots x_{N})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{y}=(y_{1},\ldots y_{N})$
\end_inset

 independently.
 Each value is then replaced according to its position after the sorting
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
x_{i}^{\mathrm{sorted}}\rightarrow\tilde{x}_{i}\equiv\frac{i}{N},\quad y_{i}^{\mathrm{sorted}}\rightarrow\tilde{y}_{i}\equiv\frac{i}{N}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Second, from the flattened distributions an 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times n$
\end_inset

 histogram 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 with equidistant binning is generated.
 If the distributions of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 are independent, the histogram content is expected to be compatible with
 a two-dimensional uniform distribution.
 To quantify the independence hypothesis a 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi^{2}$
\end_inset

-test is performed by calculating
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\chi^{2}=\sum_{i}\sum_{j}\frac{\left(h_{ij}-e\right)^{2}}{\sigma_{e}^{2}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

with the expectation value and its uncertainty for the flat hypothesis
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
e=\frac{N}{n^{2}},\qquad\sigma_{e}=\sqrt{\frac{N}{n^{2}}}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The probability of this hypothesis follows a 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi^{2}$
\end_inset

-distribution with 
\begin_inset Formula $n^{2}-(2n-1)$
\end_inset

 degrees of freedom.
 The additional 
\begin_inset Formula $2n-1$
\end_inset

 degrees of freedom are not present due to the copula transformation in
 the first step.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The algorithm is fed with over 700 variables.
 This includes the transverse momentum 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{\mathrm{T}}$
\end_inset

, the polar angle 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

, the pseudorapidity 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta$
\end_inset

 and energy 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 of each reconstructed object.
 Additionally, more variables are calculated by choosing two particles and
 calculating their 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta p_{\mathrm{T}}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\eta$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\phi$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula ${\textstyle \Delta R=\sqrt{\Delta\eta^{2}+\Delta\phi^{2}}}$
\end_inset

, included angle, invariant mass, and total transverse momentum 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P_{\mathrm{T}}^{ij}=\sqrt{\left(p_{x}^{i}+p_{x}^{j}\right)^{2}+\left(p_{y}^{i}+p_{y}^{j}\right)^{2}}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The search for independent variables to 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos\theta_{\mathrm{B.,\, X}}$
\end_inset

 is performed with the Powheg sample with approximately 
\begin_inset Formula $55000$
\end_inset

 events.
 Each bin in the histogram 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 is filled with a statistically sufficient amount of simulated events of
 approximately 
\begin_inset Formula $100$
\end_inset

.
 For the Powheg sample, this leads to 
\begin_inset Formula ${\textstyle \frac{55000}{100}}\approx23^{2}$
\end_inset

 bins in 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $484$
\end_inset

 degrees of freedom.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Confidence is gained in the algorithm as it first suggests the 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 angles of all particles to be the most independent variables.
 Those variables are expected to be most independent to 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos\theta_{\mathrm{B.,\, X}}$
\end_inset

 due to the detector geometry.
 As these angles do not add any discrimination power between signal and
 background processes, they are omitted.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The complete ranking is listed in the appendix.
 The ranking is obtained by testing each variable for independence against
 the six 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos\theta_{\mathrm{B,\, X}}$
\end_inset

 angles and summing up the resulting 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi^{2}$
\end_inset

 values.
 This analysis uses only the first 100 variables.
 Figure 
