\begin_layout Section
Unfolding
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A signal-enriched phase space is obtained by using a multivariate discriminator.
 Smearing effects, finite resolution, the acceptance of the detector and
 the event selection change the differential 
\begin_inset Formula ${\textstyle \frac{\mathrm{d}\sigma}{\mathrm{d}\cos\theta_{\mathrm{B,\, X}}}}$
\end_inset

-shape.
 Thus, the calculation of the top quark spin asymmetries from the 
\begin_inset Formula ${\textstyle \frac{\mathrm{d}\sigma}{\mathrm{d}\cos\theta_{\mathrm{B,\, X}}}}$
\end_inset

-distributions can not yet be compared to the theory prediction.
 Unfolding is a method to correct for these effects and to allow a comparison
 with the theoretical prediction.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose a true distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 leads to a measured distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $g(y)$
\end_inset

 due to smearing, finite resolution, and acceptance effects.
 This can be modeled by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
g(y)=\int f(x)A(y,\, x)\mathrm{d}x\label{eq:folding-integral}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which is called a Fredholm integral equation of the first kind 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "volkerBobel"

\end_inset

.
 The function 
\begin_inset Formula $A(y,\, x)$
\end_inset

 encodes the behavior of the detector for a variable transformation 
\begin_inset Formula $x\rightarrow y$
\end_inset

.
 This transformation may even include non-linear detector responses.
 One is then interested in solving this equation to obtain the true distribution
 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 from the measured one 
\begin_inset Formula $g(y)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By discretizing the distributions within histograms, equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:folding-integral"

\end_inset

 can be written as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\vec{y}=A\cdot\vec{x},\label{eq:unfolding}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{y}$
\end_inset

 denotes the measured binned distribution and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}$
\end_inset

 denotes the true binned distributions.
 The matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is called 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

response matrix
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and encodes the effects of the detector.
 An element 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{ij}$
\end_inset

 of the response matrix is proportional to the probability that a true value
 in bin 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 is measured in bin 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 The response matrix can be constructed by using a simulated event sample
 in which both distributions 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{y}$
\end_inset

 are accessible.
 Therefore, the unfolding relies on the correctness of the detector simulation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:unfolding"

\end_inset

 can simply be solved by
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\vec{x}=A^{-1}\vec{y}.\label{eq:unfolding-solution}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

However, this solution can be very unstable because unfolding is actual
 an ill-posed problem 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "volkerBobel"

\end_inset

.
 An example is shown in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Oscillations"

\end_inset

.
 Here, using the true distribution 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:true-dist"

\end_inset

 and the measured distribution 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:measured-dist"

\end_inset

 (solid line), a response matrix is generated.
 The dashed distribution is then subjected to unfolding by inversion of
 the response matrix.
 The result is shown in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:oscillation-dist"

\end_inset

.
 Large oscillations can appear if one tries to unfold other distributions
 with an inverted response matrix.
 Only the measured distribution which is used to construct the matrix does
 not inherit these oscillations.
 The oscillations can already arise if a distribution from a statistical
 fluctuation of the used measured distribution is unfolded.
 The origin of these oscillations is described in the following.
\end_layout

