\begin_layout Standard
The singular value decomposition (SVD) helps to understand the problem 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "svdunfolding"

\end_inset

.
 SVD can be used to decompose even non-quadratic matrices 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 into the form
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
A=U\cdot D\cdot V
\end{equation}

\end_inset

with the diagonal matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

.
 The diagonal elements 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{ii}$
\end_inset

 are called singular values.
 For the unfolding problem, they are per convention normalized as 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{11}=1$
\end_inset

 and sorted as 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{ii}>D_{i+1,\, i+1}>0$
\end_inset

.
 As a simple example, the response matrix 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
A=\frac{1}{2}\cdot\left(\begin{array}{cc}
1+\epsilon & 1-\epsilon\\
1-\epsilon & 1+\epsilon
\end{array}\right),\qquad\epsilon\in[0;\,1]\label{eq:example-detector}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

of a fictitious detector with the parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon$
\end_inset

 shall be analyzed.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon$
\end_inset

 goes to 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 the detector is able to measure a variable in both bins ideally.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

, both bins are smeared until they are indistinguishable by the detector.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The SVD applied to 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 leads to the solution
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\vec{x} & =\underbrace{\left(U\cdot D\cdot V\right)^{-1}}_{A^{-1}}\cdot\vec{y}\\
 & =\underbrace{\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\left(\begin{array}{cc}
1 & 1\\
1 & -1
\end{array}\right)}_{=V^{-1}}\cdot\underbrace{\left(\begin{array}{cc}
1 & 0\\
0 & {\textstyle \frac{1}{\epsilon}}
\end{array}\right)}_{=D^{-1}}\cdot\underbrace{\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\left(\begin{array}{cc}
1 & 1\\
1 & -1
\end{array}\right)}_{=U^{-1}}\cdot\left(\begin{array}{c}
y_{1}\\
y_{2}
\end{array}\right)\\
 & =\underbrace{1}_{D_{11}^{-1}}\cdot\frac{1}{2}\left(\begin{array}{c}
1\\
1
\end{array}\right)\cdot\left(y_{1}+y_{2}\right)+\underbrace{\frac{1}{\epsilon}}_{D_{22}^{-1}}\cdot\frac{1}{2}\underbrace{\left(\begin{array}{c}
1\\
-1
\end{array}\right)}_{\mathrm{anti\, correlation}}\cdot\left(y_{1}-y_{2}\right)\label{eq:anticorr}
\end{align}

\end_inset

for the unfolding problem.
 The last term in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:anticorr"

\end_inset

 induces a negative correlation between 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 If the singular value 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{22}$
\end_inset

 goes to zero, this term leads to oscillations.
 The oscillation term dominates the first term in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:anticorr"

\end_inset

 through the inequation 
\begin_inset Formula ${\textstyle \frac{1}{D_{11}}}<{\textstyle \frac{1}{D_{22}}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In conclusion, this means that differences between two bins get unphysically
 amplified through a simple inversion if the response matrix contains very
 small singular values.
 In order to avoid unphysically large oscillations the unfolding procedure
 is regularized.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Regularization
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A simple regularization method is performed by a singular value decomposition
 of the response matrix and dropping a certain amount of SVDs during the
 matrix inversion.
 This method is often called 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

SVD Unfolding
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 The regularization can be referred to as a hard cut-off which leads to
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
x_{i}\rightarrow\tilde{x}_{i} & =\sum_{k}^{n}\tilde{A}_{ik}^{-1}\cdot x_{k}\\
 & =\sum_{k}^{n}\left(\sum_{j}^{\tau}V_{ij}^{-1}\frac{1}{D_{jj}}U_{jk}^{-1}\right)\cdot x_{k},
\end{align}

\end_inset

where the parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau<n$
\end_inset

 denotes the index of the smallest considered singular value 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{\tau\tau}$
\end_inset

.
 The regularized solution 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{x}_{i}$
\end_inset

 inherits a bias.
 The choice of the parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 defines a priori the maximal curvature of the unfolded distribution.
 Therefore, regularized unfolding can only be applied if a sufficiently
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

smooth
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 unfolded distribution is expected a priori, e.g.
 from theory.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However, this analysis uses a more sophisticated regularization method 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "tunfold"

\end_inset

.
 The solution 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}$
\end_inset

 of equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:unfolding-solution"

\end_inset

 can be rewritten as the minimization of the function
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\chi^{2}=\left(\vec{y}-A\vec{x}\right)^{\mathrm{T}}\cdot V_{y}^{-1}\cdot\left(\vec{y}-A\vec{x}\right)+\mathfrak{R}(\vec{x},\,\vec{y}),\label{eq:chi2-unfolding}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{y}$
\end_inset

 denotes the covariance matrix of 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{y}$
\end_inset

.
 If the measured distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{y}$
\end_inset

 does not contain correlated entries, the covariance matrix can be expressed
 as 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{y,\, jj}=\sqrt{y_{j}}$
\end_inset

.
 This assumes Poisson uncertainties.
 The optional term 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathfrak{R}(\vec{x},\,\vec{y})=\tau^{2}\vec{x}\cdot L^{\mathrm{T}}L\cdot\vec{x}+\left(\sum y_{i}-\epsilon^{\mathrm{T}}\vec{x}\right)\label{eq:reg}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

is added to suppress large fluctuations.
 The matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 approximates numerically the second derivatives from 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}$
\end_inset

.
 It utilizes the general formula
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\mathrm{d}^{2}f(x)}{\mathrm{d}x^{2}}\approx\frac{x_{i+1}-2\cdot x_{i}+x_{i-1}}{h^{2}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

for the second derivative of a discretizing generic function 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 with the step width 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "numericalrep"

\end_inset

.
 Additionally, the second term in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:reg"

\end_inset

 invokes a constrain on the total number of events in the unfolded distribution
 by using the diagonal efficiency matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, by minimizing equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:chi2-unfolding"

\end_inset

 the additional term 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{R}$
\end_inset

 suppresses solutions 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}$
\end_inset

 with large curvatures and corrects simultaneously for acceptance effects.
 Oscillating solutions have high curvatures and are therefore rejected.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The regularization parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 controls the influence of the second derivatives in the minimization and
 has to be chosen carefully.
 If it is chosen too small, unphysical oscillations are not sufficiently
 suppressed.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 is chosen too large, the solution is biased towards a solution with the
 smallest curvature.
 This regularization method is a special case of the Tikhonov-Phillips regulariz
ation method.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this analysis, the optimal value of the parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 is estimated by evaluating the correlations in the unfolded solution.
 The procedure is demonstrated for a similar detector given in equation
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:example-detector"

\end_inset

.
 Here, the detector is extended to measure in four different bins.
 The resulting correlations in the unfolded distribution are calculated
 as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The covariance matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{x}$
\end_inset

 of the unfolded distribution is obtained by propagation of uncertainty
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
V_{x}=J\cdot V_{y}\cdot J^{\mathrm{T}}=\tilde{A}^{-1}\cdot V_{y}\cdot\left(\tilde{A}^{-1}\right)^{\mathrm{T}},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the Jacobi matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

 is equivalent to the regularized inverted response matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{A}^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
 Then, the correlation between two bins 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 is given by
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\rho_{ij}=\frac{\mathrm{cov}_{ij}}{\sqrt{\mathrm{var}_{i}\cdot\mathrm{var}_{j}}}=\frac{V_{x,\, ij}}{\sqrt{V_{x,\, ii}\cdot V_{x,\, jj}}}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

In this particular analysis, the correlation coefficients are averaged as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
"\langle\rho_{i,i+j}\rangle"\equiv\frac{1}{n-j-1}\cdot\sum_{i}^{n-j-1}\rho_{i,i+j}.
\]

\end_inset

Negative correlations between directly adjacent bins lead to 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle\rho_{i,i+1}\rangle<0$
\end_inset

.
 This is an indicator for the previously observed unphysical oscillations.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Unregularized-correlations"

\end_inset

 shows the averaged correlation for a simple matrix inversion (
\begin_inset Formula $\tau=0$
\end_inset

) against the detector parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

